    "Lang was also published many times in the Architectural Review, where Pevsner served as an editor.</p>\n\n<p>During her time in London, Lang also worked extensively with historians at the Warburg Institute, where she published in the early \"astonishing variety and scope of architectural studies\" including seminal studies by <a href=\"/wittkowerr\">Rudolf Wittkower</a>, <a href=\"/ackermanj\">James Ackerman</a> and <a href=\"/kublerg\">George Kubler</a> (Eck).": [
        [
            70,
            77,
            [
                "Pester",
                "Evener",
                "Eisner"
            ]
        ]
    ],
    "In 1950, her work <em>The early publications of the temples at Paestum</em> was published within the annual, collaborative Journal of the Warburg and Courtauld Institutes, further demonstrating her ties to the institute.</p>\n\n<p>Lang\u2019s residency in England had a measurable influence on the subjects of her writings, evident in works such as <em>The Principles of the Gothic revival in England</em> (1966) and <em>The genesis of English landscape garden</em> (1973).": [],
    "Overall, the majority of Lang\u2019s scholarly works are featured in larger works by other authors, and she never published her own book.": [],
    "Viewed inferior as a female art historian, a significant portion of her writing in these larger works remains uncredited.": [],
    "After some time in England, Lang ultimately moved to Israel where she would live until her death, while still making frequent trips to England.</p>": []
